      <h1 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900">
        In-Home Care & Staying Home Longer
      </h1>

      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-700 max-w-3xl">
        Many older adults prefer to stay in their own homes for as long as possible. This page
        explains the different kinds of in-home care, what each type can and cannot do, how they
        are paid for, and how seniors can build a support system that helps them stay independent
        longer. All information is based on publicly available sources.
      </p>

      <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-600">
        This page is educational only and does not promote or endorse any specific provider.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- What In-Home Care Includes -->
    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">What “in-home care” actually means</h2>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-700">
        In-home care can range from a few hours a week of light help to full-time live-in support.
        It is not a single service — it is a set of different roles and agencies.
      </p>

      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-sm text-slate-700 space-y-1">
        <li><strong>Companion care</strong> — conversation, light help, errands, meal preparation.</li>
        <li><strong>Homemaker services</strong> — laundry, cleaning, organizing, chores.</li>
        <li><strong>Personal care aides</strong> — help with bathing, dressing, grooming, toileting.</li>
        <li><strong>Home health</strong> — skilled nursing ordered by a doctor (short-term).</li>
        <li><strong>Private caregivers</strong> — independent workers hired directly by families.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">
        These roles have different rules and payment options, which vary by state.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Home Health vs Personal Care -->
    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">
        Home health (medical) vs. personal care (non-medical)
      </h2>

      <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">
        These two categories are often mixed together — but they are very different:
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">Home health</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-slate-700 space-y-1">
            <li>Short-term and medically necessary</li>
            <li>Requires a doctor’s order</li>
            <li>Includes nurses, therapists, and wound care</li>
            <li>Covered by Medicare for limited periods</li>
            <li>Does NOT provide daily housekeeping or long-term care</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">Personal care & companion services</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-slate-700 space-y-1">
            <li>Help with daily activities and routines</li>
            <li>No medical tasks</li>
            <li>Often private pay</li>
            <li>Sometimes covered by Medicaid HCBS waivers</li>
            <li>Flexible—can be a few hours or much more</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Cost Factors -->
    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">
        What in-home care costs (based on public estimates)
      </h2>

      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-700">
        Costs depend on location, agency structure, caregiver experience, and hours needed.
        Publicly reported national averages show:
      </p>

      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-sm text-slate-700 space-y-1">
        <li>Companion care: often $20–$30/hour</li>
        <li>Personal care: $22–$35/hour</li>
        <li>Overnight or 24-hour care: varies widely</li>
        <li>Live-in caregivers: flat daily/weekly rates</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">
        Most in-home care is <strong>private pay</strong>, but some Medicaid programs offer limited hours.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Medicaid Home and Community Based Services -->
    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Medicaid home and community-based services (HCBS)</h2>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-700">
        Some seniors may qualify for Medicaid-supported caregiver hours under HCBS waivers.
        These programs vary widely:
      </p>

      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-sm text-slate-700 space-y-1">
        <li>strict eligibility rules</li>
        <li>medical and financial requirements</li>
        <li>limited hours compared to private pay</li>
        <li>waitlists in many states</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">
        Even a small number of hours can help families support independence longer.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Staying Home Longer -->
    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Practical ways to stay home longer</h2>

      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-700">
        Many people can safely remain home by layering simple supports. These examples come from
        public programs and common practices:
      </p>

      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-sm text-slate-700 space-y-1">
        <li><strong>Meal support:</strong> Meals on Wheels, congregate meal sites, grocery delivery.</li>
        <li><strong>Errands:</strong> pharmacy pickup, scheduling appointments, transportation help.</li>
        <li><strong>Safety tools:</strong> fall detection wearables, stove or door sensors.</li>
        <li><strong>Household support:</strong> laundry services, cleaning, lawn care.</li>
        <li><strong>Medication tools:</strong> reminders, simple pill organizers, timed dispensers.</li>
        <li><strong>Social connection:</strong> video calls, senior centers, adult day programs.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">
        The key is designing supports around the person — not forcing them into a facility before it’s truly needed.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Family Coordination -->
    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Coordinating with family</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">
        Staying home often works best when family understands what’s needed and how to share tasks.
        Tools like shared calendars, reminders, and simple weekly check-ins can reduce confusion
        and prevent burnout.
      </p>

      <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">
        Families don’t have to provide all care — but early communication prevents panic decisions
        during a crisis.
      </p>
    </section>

